{"title_page": "I Believe in a Thing Called Love", "text_new": "{{short description|2003 single by The Darkness}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Believe in a Thing Called Love\n| cover      = I Believe in a Thing Called Love single cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Darkness (band)|The Darkness]]\n| album      = [[Permission to Land]]\n| B-side     =\n* \"Makin Out\"\n* \"Physical Sex\"\n* \"Out of My Hands\"\n| released   = 7 July 2003\n| format     =\n* [[CD single]]\n* [[DVD single]]\n* [[7\" vinyl]]\n* [[music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2002-03\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Hard rock]]\n* [[glam rock]]\n* [[glam metal]]\n| length     = 3:40\n| label      = [[Must Destroy]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Justin Hawkins]]\n* [[Dan Hawkins (musician)|Dan Hawkins]]\n* [[Ed Graham]]\n* [[Frankie Poullain]]\n| producer   = Pedro Ferreira\n| prev_title = [[Growing on Me]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Christmas Time (Don't Let the Bells End)]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n\"'''I Believe in a Thing Called Love'''\" is a song by [[United Kingdom|English]] [[rock music|rock]] band [[The Darkness (band)|The Darkness]], released as the third single from their debut studio album, ''[[Permission to Land]]''.\n\nWhen released as a single in September 2003, it peaked at number two in the [[UK Singles Chart]], just behind [[The Black Eyed Peas]]' \"[[Where Is the Love?]]\". Lead singer Justin Hawkins performs much of the song in [[falsetto]].\n\nIt was named the 276th best track of the 2000s by [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7685-the-top-500-tracks-of-the-2000s-500-201/|title=The Top 500 Tracks of the 2000s: 500-201|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" was originally issued as a 3-track EP in August 2002; however, as only a small number of copies were printed, it was ineligible to chart. The EP also included early versions of \"Love on the Rocks With No Ice\" and \"Love Is Only a Feeling\". When released as a single in September 2003, it was beaten to number one by [[The Black Eyed Peas]]' \"[[Where Is the Love?]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=6598|title=I Believe In A Thing Called Love Songfacts|publisher=}}</ref> Lead singer [[Justin Hawkins]] performs much of the song in [[head voice]]. In March 2005, [[Q magazine|''Q'' magazine]] placed \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" at number 47 in its list of the 101 Greatest Guitar Tracks. It is also placed 493 on The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born on ''Blender'' magazine. Most recently, it ranked at 276 of ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s 500 Top Tracks of the 2000s<ref>[http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7685-the-top-500-tracks-of-the-2000s-500-201/5 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820132123/http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7685-the-top-500-tracks-of-the-2000s-500-201/5 |date=20 August 2009 }}</ref> and was ranked number one for ''Classic Rock Magazine''{{'}}s list of \"The Greatest Rock Songs of the Noughties\". The song was also named the 94th best hard rock song of all time by VH1.<ref>{{cite web|title=spreadit.org music |url=http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |access-date=4 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212180319/http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |archive-date=12 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A live version of the song, recorded at [[Concerts at Knebworth House|Knebworth House]] in [[Knebworth]], [[Hertfordshire]] in 2003, was featured as a B-side to the group's Christmas single, \"Christmas Time (Don't Let the Bells End)\". The song peaked at number 67 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Digital Songs]] chart in February 2012 after [[Justin Hawkins]] appeared in a commercial during [[Super Bowl XLVI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/samsungmobileusa?v=CgfknZidYq0|title=YouTube|publisher=}}</ref> It has sold 647,000 copies in the U.S. as of February 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/508231/the-darkness-declares-nothings-gonna-stop-us-on-comeback-single |title=The Darkness Declares 'Nothing's Gonna Stop Us' on Comeback Single|date=1 February 2012 |author= Jason Lipshutz |work=Billboard }}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for the song was designed to launch the band onto the U.S. market.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/599451711.html?dids=599451711:599451711&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+02%2C+2004&author=Richard+Harrington&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=The+Darkness+Falls+on+U.S.&pqatl=google | title=The Darkness Falls on U.S | first=Richard | last=Harrington | date=2 April 2004}}</ref> Directed by Alex Smith, the band are shown on a spaceship, performing and battling aliens and monsters.<ref name=\"xfm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/Article.asp?id=13062&spid=42820 |title=The Darkness 'I Believe In A Thing Called Love' |publisher=Xfm |date= |accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/projo/access/600861111.html?dids=600861111:600861111&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+01%2C+2004&author=Rick+Massimo&pub=The+Providence+Journal&desc=Music+-+Music+scene+-+Darkness%3A+Rock+with+the+benefit+of+hindsight&pqatl=google | work=The Providence Journal | title=Music - Music scene - Darkness: Rock with the benefit of hindsight | first=Rick | last=Massimo | date=1 April 2004}}</ref> It uses the [[single version]], which is a key upward than the album version.\n\n==Track listings==\n'''CD single'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Makin' Out\" \u2013 3:39\n# \"Physical Sex\" \u2013 3:33\n\n'''Digital EP'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Makin' Out\" \u2013 3:39\n# \"Physical Sex\" \u2013 3:33\n# \"Out of My Hands\" \u2013 3:33\n\n'''DVD single'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Out of My Hands\" \u2013 3:33\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (music video) \u2013 3:50\n\n'''7\" vinyl'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Makin' Out\" \u2013 3:39\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2003\u20132004)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|40|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|2|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada Rock Top 30 ([[Radio & Records]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2004/RR-2004-04-16.pdf|title=RR Canada Rock Top 30|p=59|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|37|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|47|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|songid=10264|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|5|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|15|year=2003|week=47|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|12|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|10|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|14|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|2|date=20031004|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|8|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|2|date=20031004|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKindie|1|date=20031004|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKrock|1|date=20031004|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]]\n|9\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Top 40]]\n|35\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2003)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|UK Singles (Official Charts Company)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukchartsplus.co.uk/ChartsPlusYE2003.pdf|title=The Official UK Singles Chart 2003|work=[[UKChartsPlus]]|format=PDF|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n|33\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2004)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|New Zealand (Recorded Music NZ)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=2085|title=End of Year Charts 2004|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n|49\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Darkness|title=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|award=Gold|relyear=2003|certyear=2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Hayseed Dixie]] on their 2004 album ''[[Let There Be Rockgrass]]''.\n* [[Damien Dempsey]] on the 2003 charity album ''[[Even Better Than the Real Thing Vol. 1]]''.\n* [[Shayne Ward]] as a contestant on ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2005.\n* [[Lemar]] on the 2007 [[BBC Radio 1]] ''[[Radio 1's Live Lounge|Live Lounge]]'' album.\n* [[Artist vs. Poet]] on the 2010 compilation album ''Rockin' Romance II''.\n* ''Nitritt'' on their debut EP ''Gallery of Time''.\n* [[List of The X Factor finalists (UK series 8)#Johnny Robinson|Johnny Robinson]] as a contestant on ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=76ZZs17d3Jg|title=YouTube|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Giant Bomb|Brad Shoemaker]] at [[PAX (event)|PAX East]] 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9JmenwVvbgc|title=Brad totally believes in a thing called love|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n* [[Panic! at the Disco]] in various live shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ClBPqREMgqg|title=Panic! At the disco - I Believe In A Thing Called Love (Cover) - Center stage LIVE|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n* [[Dylan Everett]] and Olivia Scriven on ''[[Degrassi]]'' in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i-jQp1e5nqI|title=Degrassi - Maya & Campbell - Karaoke|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n* Swedish singer Edson in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fm4v2.orf.at/station/182344/main|title=fm4v2.ORF.at / Sunny Side Up Vol. 4|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Adam Lambert]] and [[Chris Colfer]] in ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' episode \"[[Frenemies (Glee)|Frenemies]]\", in 2014.\n* [[Scott Bradlee]] and Postmodern Jukebox released a [[New Orleans]] [[jazz]] version of the song in 2015, featuring Maiya Sykes.\n* [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]] covered the song on their ''Roots & Rock 'N' Roll'' EP in 2015.\n* [[Delta Goodrem]] on her 2016 album ''[[Wings of the Wild]]''.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThis song was featured as a playable track on the music video games ''[[Karaoke Revolution Volume 2]]'' and ''[[Guitar Hero On Tour: Decades]]''; as [[Diegesis|source music]] in an episode of ''[[The Bill]]''; and as part of the soundtracks for the films ''[[Bridget Jones: The Edge of Reason (film)|Bridget Jones: The Edge of Reason]] and [[Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates]].'' The song was also featured on the original version of ''[[SingStar]]''. It is featured in both ''[[Rocksmith]]'' and ''[[Rock Band 3]]'' as downloadable content. The song was featured in a 2012 commercial during [[Super Bowl XLVI]], for the [[Samsung Galaxy Note (original)|Samsung Galaxy Note]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowyourmobile.com/blog/1234393/samsung_pokes_fun_at_apple_in_advert_again.html|title=Samsung pokes fun at Apple in advert... again|work=Know Your Mobile}}</ref> This propelled the song to the number one spot on U.S. iTunes rock chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2012/02/the-darkness-talk-super-bowl-commercial|title=The Darkness Talk About Their \"Surreal, Last Minute\" Super Bowl Commercial|work=Fuse}}</ref> The song also appeared in an [[Apple Music]] commercial featuring pop singer [[Taylor Swift]] in 2016. The song was also used by [[Tye Dillinger]] for a theme song for a little while, while he was in [[Ohio Valley Wrestling]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|darkness|i-believe-in-a-thing-called-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Darkness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Believe In A Thing Called Love}}\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:The Darkness (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Justin Hawkins]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dan Hawkins (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Frankie Poullain]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ed Graham]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2003 single by The Darkness}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Believe in a Thing Called Love\n| cover      = I Believe in a Thing Called Love single cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Darkness (band)|The Darkness]]\n| album      = [[Permission to Land]]\n| B-side     =\n* \"Makin Out\"\n* \"Physical Sex\"\n* \"Out of My Hands\"\n| released   = 7 July 2003\n| format     =\n* [[CD single]]\n* [[DVD single]]\n* [[7\" vinyl]]\n* [[music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2002-03\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Hard rock]]\n* [[glam rock]]\n* [[glam metal]]\n| length     = 3:40\n| label      = [[Must Destroy]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Justin Hawkins]]\n* [[Dan Hawkins (musician)|Dan Hawkins]]\n* [[Ed Graham]]\n* [[Frankie Poullain]]\n| producer   = Pedro Ferreira\n| prev_title = [[Growing on Me]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Christmas Time (Don't Let the Bells End)]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n\"'''I Believe in a Thing Called Love'''\" is a song by [[United Kingdom|English]] [[rock music|rock]] band [[The Darkness (band)|The Darkness]], released as the third single from their debut studio album, ''[[Permission to Land]]''.\n\nWhen released as a single in September 2003, it peaked at number two in the [[UK Singles Chart]], just behind [[The Black Eyed Peas]]' \"[[Where Is the Love?]]\". Lead singer Justin Hawkins performs much of the song in [[falsetto]].\n\nIt was named the 276th best track of the 2000s by [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7685-the-top-500-tracks-of-the-2000s-500-201/|title=The Top 500 Tracks of the 2000s: 500-201|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" was originally issued as a 3-track EP in August 2002; however, as only a small number of copies were printed, it was ineligible to chart. The EP also included early versions of \"Love on the Rocks With No Ice\" and \"Love Is Only a Feeling\". When released as a single in September 2003, it was beaten to number one by [[The Black Eyed Peas]]' \"[[Where Is the Love?]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=6598|title=I Believe In A Thing Called Love Songfacts|publisher=}}</ref> Lead singer [[Justin Hawkins]] performs much of the song in [[head voice]]. In March 2005, [[Q magazine|''Q'' magazine]] placed \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" at number 47 in its list of the 101 Greatest Guitar Tracks. It is also placed 493 on The 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born on ''Blender'' magazine. Most recently, it ranked at 276 of ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s 500 Top Tracks of the 2000s<ref>[http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7685-the-top-500-tracks-of-the-2000s-500-201/5 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090820132123/http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7685-the-top-500-tracks-of-the-2000s-500-201/5 |date=20 August 2009 }}</ref> and was ranked number one for ''Classic Rock Magazine''{{'}}s list of \"The Greatest Rock Songs of the Noughties\". The song was also named the 94th best hard rock song of all time by VH1.<ref>{{cite web|title=spreadit.org music |url=http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |access-date=4 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212180319/http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |archive-date=12 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A live version of the song, recorded at [[Concerts at Knebworth House|Knebworth House]] in [[Knebworth]], [[Hertfordshire]] in 2003, was featured as a B-side to the group's Christmas single, \"Christmas Time (Don't Let the Bells End)\". The song peaked at number 67 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Digital Songs]] chart in February 2012 after [[Justin Hawkins]] appeared in a commercial during [[Super Bowl XLVI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/samsungmobileusa?v=CgfknZidYq0|title=YouTube|publisher=}}</ref> It has sold 647,000 copies in the U.S. as of February 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/508231/the-darkness-declares-nothings-gonna-stop-us-on-comeback-single |title=The Darkness Declares 'Nothing's Gonna Stop Us' on Comeback Single|date=1 February 2012 |author= Jason Lipshutz |work=Billboard }}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for the song was designed to launch the band onto the U.S. market.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/599451711.html?dids=599451711:599451711&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+02%2C+2004&author=Richard+Harrington&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=The+Darkness+Falls+on+U.S.&pqatl=google | title=The Darkness Falls on U.S | first=Richard | last=Harrington | date=2 April 2004}}</ref> Directed by Alex Smith, the band are shown on a spaceship, performing and battling aliens and monsters.<ref name=\"xfm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/Article.asp?id=13062&spid=42820 |title=The Darkness 'I Believe In A Thing Called Love' |publisher=Xfm |date= |accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/projo/access/600861111.html?dids=600861111:600861111&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+01%2C+2004&author=Rick+Massimo&pub=The+Providence+Journal&desc=Music+-+Music+scene+-+Darkness%3A+Rock+with+the+benefit+of+hindsight&pqatl=google | work=The Providence Journal | title=Music - Music scene - Darkness: Rock with the benefit of hindsight | first=Rick | last=Massimo | date=1 April 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\n'''CD single'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Makin' Out\" \u2013 3:39\n# \"Physical Sex\" \u2013 3:33\n\n'''Digital EP'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Makin' Out\" \u2013 3:39\n# \"Physical Sex\" \u2013 3:33\n# \"Out of My Hands\" \u2013 3:33\n\n'''DVD single'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Out of My Hands\" \u2013 3:33\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (music video) \u2013 3:50\n\n'''7\" vinyl'''\n# \"I Believe in a Thing Called Love\" (single version) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Makin' Out\" \u2013 3:39\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2003\u20132004)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|40|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|2|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada Rock Top 30 ([[Radio & Records]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2004/RR-2004-04-16.pdf|title=RR Canada Rock Top 30|p=59|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|37|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|47|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|songid=10264|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|5|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|15|year=2003|week=47|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|12|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|10|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|14|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|2|date=20031004|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|8|artist=The Darkness|song=I Believe in a Thing Called Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|2|date=20031004|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKindie|1|date=20031004|rowheader=true|accessdate=9 December 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKr