{"title_page": "H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands", "text_new": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c Archipelago (archipel des Pirates)\n| native_name      = Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c\n| sobriquet        = \n| image_name       = M\u1ed9t ph\u1ea7n qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| image_caption    = A part of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands\n| image_alt        = A part of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands\n| map =  Vietnam\n| location         = [[Gulf of Thailand]]\n| coordinates      = {{Coord|10|10|08|N|104|20|00|E|region:VN|name=Ha Tien Islands|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      = \n| waterbody        = \n| total_islands    = 16 (14)\n| major_islands    = h\u00f2n \u0110\u1ed1c\n| area_km2         = 11\n| area_footnotes   = \n| rank             = \n| length_km        = \n| length_footnotes = \n| width_km         = \n| width_footnotes  =\n| coastline_km     = \n| coastline_footnotes = \n| elevation_m      = \n| elevation_footnotes = \n| highest_mount    = \n| Country_heading  = \n| country          = Vietnam\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[Provinces of Vietnam|Province]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Ki\u00ean Giang Province|Ki\u00ean Giang]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[District-level town (Vietnam)|District-level town]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = [[Rural commune (Vietnam)|Commune]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2         = Ti\u00ean H\u1ea3i\n| demonym          = \n| population       = \n| population_as_of = \n| density_km2      = \n| density_footnotes = \n| ethnic_groups    = \n| website          = \n| additional_info  = \n}}\n\n'''H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands''' ({{lang-vi|Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean}}) is an [[archipelago]] located in the [[Gulf of Thailand]]. It constitutes Tien Hai Commune of [[H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean]], [[Ki\u00ean Giang Province]], [[Vietnam]]. Since [[pirate]]s used to plague the region in the past, another popular name for the islands is '''H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c Islands''' ({{lang|vi|Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c}}, literally \"Pirate Islands\").\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:\u00c2u thuy\u1ec1n qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean.jpg|250px|thumb|left|A dock in H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands. Photo: \u0110\u1ed7 Do\u00e3n Ho\u00e0ng.]]\nThe H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands lie off the coast of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, to the east of [[Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c]] Island. The archipelago is in turn {{convert|11|nmi|km mi}}, {{convert|9.7|nmi|km mi}} and {{convert|16|nmi|km mi}} away from the coast of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, the mainland of Vietnam and Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c Island.<ref name=\"badm\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news |title=\u0110\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c \u2013 Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean: Ti\u1ec1m n\u0103ng t\u1eeb bi\u1ec3n |url=http://www.baoanhdatmui.vn/vcms/html/news_detail.php?nid=8685 |author=\u0110\u00e0o |publisher=B\u00e1o \u1ea3nh M\u0169i |date=February 23, 2009 |accessdate=December 2, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53PfR4I?url=http://www.baoanhdatmui.vn/vcms/html/news_detail.php?nid=8685 |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There are in total 16 islands<ref>{{in lang|vi}} {{cite book |title=S\u1ed5 tay \u0111\u1ecba danh Vi\u1ec7t Nam |author=Nguy\u1ec5n D\u01b0\u1ee3c; Trung H\u1ea3i |year=2008 |publisher=Viet Nam Education Publishing House |page=117}}</ref> (other statistics: 14<ref name=\"tp\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news|url=http://www.tienphong.vn/xa-hoi/30461/Vo-chong-%E2%80%9CRobinson%E2%80%9D-tren-quan-dao-Hai-tac.html |title=V\u1ee3 ch\u1ed3ng \"Robinson\" tr\u00ean qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |author=H\u1ed3ng L\u0129nh |publisher=Ti\u1ec1n phong online |date=December 1, 2005 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53ZzZYz?url=http://www.tienphong.vn/xa-hoi/30461/Vo-chong-%E2%80%9CRobinson%E2%80%9D-tren-quan-dao-Hai-tac.html |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>) locating close to one another with a height of less than {{convert|100|m|ft}}, and among those, Hon Doc ({{lang|vi|h\u00f2n \u0110\u1ed1c}}) is the largest entity. The total area of the islands is {{convert|11|km2|sqmi}}<ref name=\"nghidinh\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite web|url=http://www.chinhphu.vn/portal/page/portal/chinhphu/hethongvanban?class_id=1&mode=detail&document_id=5633&category_id=0 |title=Ngh\u1ecb \u0111\u1ecbnh s\u1ed1 47/1998/N\u0110-CP c\u1ee7a Ch\u00ednh ph\u1ee7 Vi\u1ec7t Nam: Th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp th\u1ecb x\u00e3 H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean thu\u1ed9c t\u1ec9nh Ki\u00ean Giang v\u00e0 th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp c\u00e1c ph\u01b0\u1eddng thu\u1ed9c th\u1ecb x\u00e3 |publisher=Vietnam Government Web Portal |date=July 8, 1998 |accessdate=December 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53flFXN?url=http://datafile.chinhphu.vn/file-remote-v2/DownloadServlet?filePath=vbpq%2F2006%2F07%2F5656_ND47CP.RTF |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> spreading out over a water area which is {{convert|5|km|mi}} in length and {{convert|7|km|mi}} in width. Islands are composed primarily of [[Cretaceous]] [[shale]] and [[sandstone]]. [[Fresh water]] is scarce.<ref>{{in lang|vi}} {{cite web |title=H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |url=http://www.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/geograph.aspx?param=A660aWQ9MDAwMjAwMjA= |publisher=Vietnam Institute of Lexicography and Encyclopedia |accessdate=2012-12-02 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53iFzsI?url=http://www.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/geograph.aspx?param=A660aWQ9MDAwMjAwMjA= |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Etymology===\nThe H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands were also formerly known as Pirate Islands since the late 17th century and early 18th century when it served as pirates' dens. Pirates departing from here attacked and seized large merchant ships from China and the [[Western world]].<ref name=\"dtkhotin\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news|title=Nh\u1eefng chuy\u1ec7n kh\u00f3 tin \u1edf Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |author=L\u00e3ng Qu\u00e2n |url=http://dantri.com.vn/su-kien/nhung-chuyen-kho-tin-o-quan-dao-hai-tac-468240.htm |publisher=D\u00e2n tr\u00ed |date=March 29, 2011 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53mLizN?url=http://dantri.com.vn/su-kien/nhung-chuyen-kho-tin-o-quan-dao-hai-tac-468240.htm |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe islands were still known as H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c (\"Pirate\") Islands under the administration of [[South Vietnam]]. On July 28, 1958, their military mission visited the islands and later erected a sovereignty [[stele]] which still stands on the western part of the island Hon Doc.\n\n===Piracy in the past===\nDue to the rugged topography as well as the position on the important trade route, the islands were the ideal base for pirates to hide, ambush and attack crossing merchant ships for a long time. The golden era of piracy was when H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean fell into anarchy following the defeat of [[M\u1ea1c Thi\u00ean T\u1ee9]]'s administration by [[History of Thailand|Siamese]] army. Meanwhile, foreign ships with which pirate vessels mingled still had freedom of navigation in the area. Even when [[French colonial empire|the French]] occupied H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, this area was still being ravaged by piracy.<ref name=\"dtkhotin\" />\n\nThere are some rumors about [[Buried treasure#Pirate treasure|pirate treasure]] hiding in H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands. In March 1983, an American and a British departing from Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c Island secretly visited the island of Hon Tre Nho ({{lang|vi|h\u00f2n Tre Nh\u1ecf}}) in the archipelago, and they brought radios, cameras, binoculars, nautical charts,... along with themselves. After being captured by local residents, two men claimed that they had a 300-year-old map passed down by their ancestors depicting pirate treasure. In 2009, some fishermen accidentally found a quantity of ancient coins.<ref>{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news|title=Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c - \u0111\u1ea3o gi\u1ea5u v\u00e0ng? |author=S\u01a1n B\u00ecnh |url=http://www.phapluatvn.vn/so-bao-sap-toi/plcuoituan/201108/Quan-dao-Hai-Tac-dao-giau-vang-2056895/ |publisher=B\u00e1o Ph\u00e1p lu\u1eadt Vi\u1ec7t Nam \u0111i\u1ec7n t\u1eed |date=August 7, 2011 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53qmOE7?url=http://www.phapluatvn.vn/so-bao-sap-toi/plcuoituan/201108/Quan-dao-Hai-Tac-dao-giau-vang-2056895/ |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\nOnly 6 to 7 islands in the archipelago are inhabited. According to Decree No. 47/1998/ND-CP establishing the town of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean in 1998, H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands had 1,055 inhabitants.<ref name=\"nghidinh\" /> In early 2012, the island had more than 420 households with nearly 1,800 people.<ref name=\"ca\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news |title=\u0102n T\u1ebft tr\u00ean qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |author=Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh |url=http://www.cand.com.vn/vi-VN/xahoi/2012/1/164672.cand |publisher=C\u00f4ng an Nh\u00e2n d\u00e2n online |date=January 31, 2012 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53v2cLa?url=http://www.cand.com.vn/vi-VN/xahoi/2012/1/164672.cand |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nLocal residents live mainly by fishing.<ref name=\"tp\" /> In 2011, the total output of marine products was 22,000 tons. Per capita income is about 48 million [[Vietnamese \u0111\u1ed3ng|\u0111\u1ed3ng]] (nearly 2,300 U.S dollars). Furthermore, water shortage in the [[dry season]] has been solved thanks to a freshwater reservoir.<ref name=\"ca\" /> In 2007 and 2008, Kien Giang provincial government laid down a policy to lease a number of islands of Ha Tien Islands to develop marine eco-tourism.<ref name=\"badm\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Ha Tien Islands}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ha Tien Islands}}\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Ki\u00ean Giang Province]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Gulf of Thailand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c Archipelago (archipel des Pirates)\n| native_name      = Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c\n| sobriquet        = \n| image_name       = M\u1ed9t ph\u1ea7n qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| image_caption    = A part of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands\n| image_alt        = A part of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands\n| map =  Vietnam\n| location         = [[Gulf of Thailand]]\n| coordinates      = {{Coord|10|10|08|N|104|20|00|E|region:VN|name=Ha Tien Islands|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      = \n| waterbody        = \n| total_islands    = 16 (14)\n| major_islands    = h\u00f2n \u0110\u1ed1c\n| area_km2         = 11\n| area_footnotes   = \n| rank             = \n| length_km        = \n| length_footnotes = \n| width_km         = \n| width_footnotes  =\n| coastline_km     = \n| coastline_footnotes = \n| elevation_m      = \n| elevation_footnotes = \n| highest_mount    = \n| Country_heading  = \n| country          = Vietnam\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[Provinces of Vietnam|Province]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Ki\u00ean Giang Province|Ki\u00ean Giang]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[District-level town (Vietnam)|District-level town]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = [[Rural commune (Vietnam)|Commune]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2         = Ti\u00ean H\u1ea3i\n| demonym          = \n| population       = \n| population_as_of = \n| density_km2      = \n| density_footnotes = \n| ethnic_groups    = \n| website          = \n| additional_info  = \n}}\n\n'''H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands''' ({{lang-vi|Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean}}) is an [[archipelago]] located in the [[Gulf of Thailand]]. It constitutes Tien Hai Commune of [[H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean]], [[Ki\u00ean Giang Province]], [[Vietnam]]. Since [[pirate]]s used to plague the region in the past, another popular name for the islands is '''H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c Islands''' ({{lang|vi|Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c}}, literally \"Pirate Islands\"). \n\n==Geography==\n[[File:\u00c2u thuy\u1ec1n qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean.jpg|250px|thumb|left|A dock in H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands. Photo: \u0110\u1ed7 Do\u00e3n Ho\u00e0ng.]]\nThe H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands lie off the coast of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, to the east of [[Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c]] Island. The archipelago is in turn {{convert|11|nmi|km mi}}, {{convert|9.7|nmi|km mi}} and {{convert|16|nmi|km mi}} away from the coast of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, the mainland of Vietnam and Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c Island.<ref name=\"badm\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news |title=\u0110\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c \u2013 Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean: Ti\u1ec1m n\u0103ng t\u1eeb bi\u1ec3n |url=http://www.baoanhdatmui.vn/vcms/html/news_detail.php?nid=8685 |author=\u0110\u00e0o |publisher=B\u00e1o \u1ea3nh M\u0169i |date=February 23, 2009 |accessdate=December 2, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53PfR4I?url=http://www.baoanhdatmui.vn/vcms/html/news_detail.php?nid=8685 |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There are in total 16 islands<ref>{{in lang|vi}} {{cite book |title=S\u1ed5 tay \u0111\u1ecba danh Vi\u1ec7t Nam |author=Nguy\u1ec5n D\u01b0\u1ee3c; Trung H\u1ea3i |year=2008 |publisher=Viet Nam Education Publishing House |page=117}}</ref> (other statistics: 14<ref name=\"tp\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news|url=http://www.tienphong.vn/xa-hoi/30461/Vo-chong-%E2%80%9CRobinson%E2%80%9D-tren-quan-dao-Hai-tac.html |title=V\u1ee3 ch\u1ed3ng \"Robinson\" tr\u00ean qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |author=H\u1ed3ng L\u0129nh |publisher=Ti\u1ec1n phong online |date=December 1, 2005 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53ZzZYz?url=http://www.tienphong.vn/xa-hoi/30461/Vo-chong-%E2%80%9CRobinson%E2%80%9D-tren-quan-dao-Hai-tac.html |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>) locating close to one another with a height of less than {{convert|100|m|ft}}, and among those, Hon Doc ({{lang|vi|h\u00f2n \u0110\u1ed1c}}) is the largest entity. The total area of the islands is {{convert|11|km2|sqmi}}<ref name=\"nghidinh\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite web|url=http://www.chinhphu.vn/portal/page/portal/chinhphu/hethongvanban?class_id=1&mode=detail&document_id=5633&category_id=0 |title=Ngh\u1ecb \u0111\u1ecbnh s\u1ed1 47/1998/N\u0110-CP c\u1ee7a Ch\u00ednh ph\u1ee7 Vi\u1ec7t Nam: Th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp th\u1ecb x\u00e3 H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean thu\u1ed9c t\u1ec9nh Ki\u00ean Giang v\u00e0 th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp c\u00e1c ph\u01b0\u1eddng thu\u1ed9c th\u1ecb x\u00e3 |publisher=Vietnam Government Web Portal |date=July 8, 1998 |accessdate=December 3, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53flFXN?url=http://datafile.chinhphu.vn/file-remote-v2/DownloadServlet?filePath=vbpq%2F2006%2F07%2F5656_ND47CP.RTF |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> spreading out over a water area which is {{convert|5|km|mi}} in length and {{convert|7|km|mi}} in width. Islands are composed primarily of [[Cretaceous]] [[shale]] and [[sandstone]]. [[Fresh water]] is scarce.<ref>{{in lang|vi}} {{cite web |title=H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |url=http://www.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/geograph.aspx?param=A660aWQ9MDAwMjAwMjA= |publisher=Vietnam Institute of Lexicography and Encyclopedia |accessdate=2012-12-02 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53iFzsI?url=http://www.bachkhoatoanthu.gov.vn/geograph.aspx?param=A660aWQ9MDAwMjAwMjA= |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Etymology===\nThe H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands were also formerly known as Pirate Islands since the late 17th century and early 18th century when it served as pirates' dens. Pirates departing from here attacked and seized large merchant ships from China and the [[Western world]].<ref name=\"dtkhotin\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news|title=Nh\u1eefng chuy\u1ec7n kh\u00f3 tin \u1edf Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |author=L\u00e3ng Qu\u00e2n |url=http://dantri.com.vn/su-kien/nhung-chuyen-kho-tin-o-quan-dao-hai-tac-468240.htm |publisher=D\u00e2n tr\u00ed |date=March 29, 2011 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53mLizN?url=http://dantri.com.vn/su-kien/nhung-chuyen-kho-tin-o-quan-dao-hai-tac-468240.htm |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe islands were still known as H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c (\"Pirate\") Islands under the administration of [[South Vietnam]]. On July 28, 1958, their military mission visited the islands and later erected a sovereignty [[stele]] which still stands on the western part of the island Hon Doc.\n\n===Piracy in the past===\nDue to the rugged topography as well as the position on the important trade route, the islands were the ideal base for pirates to hide, ambush and attack crossing merchant ships for a long time. The golden era of piracy was when H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean fell into anarchy following the defeat of [[M\u1ea1c Thi\u00ean T\u1ee9]]'s administration by [[History of Thailand|Siamese]] army. Meanwhile, foreign ships with which pirate vessels mingled still had freedom of navigation in the area. Even when [[French colonial empire|the French]] occupied H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean, this area was still being ravaged by piracy.<ref name=\"dtkhotin\" />\n\nThere are some rumors about [[Buried treasure#Pirate treasure|pirate treasure]] hiding in H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands. In March 1983, an American and a British departing from Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c Island secretly visited the island of Hon Tre Nho ({{lang|vi|h\u00f2n Tre Nh\u1ecf}}) in the archipelago, and they brought radios, cameras, binoculars, nautical charts,... along with themselves. After being captured by local residents, two men claimed that they had a 300-year-old map passed down by their ancestors depicting pirate treasure. In 2009, some fishermen accidentally found a quantity of ancient coins.<ref>{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news|title=Qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c - \u0111\u1ea3o gi\u1ea5u v\u00e0ng? |author=S\u01a1n B\u00ecnh |url=http://www.phapluatvn.vn/so-bao-sap-toi/plcuoituan/201108/Quan-dao-Hai-Tac-dao-giau-vang-2056895/ |publisher=B\u00e1o Ph\u00e1p lu\u1eadt Vi\u1ec7t Nam \u0111i\u1ec7n t\u1eed |date=August 7, 2011 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53qmOE7?url=http://www.phapluatvn.vn/so-bao-sap-toi/plcuoituan/201108/Quan-dao-Hai-Tac-dao-giau-vang-2056895/ |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\nOnly 6 to 7 islands in the archipelago are inhabited. According to Decree No. 47/1998/ND-CP establishing the town of H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean in 1998, H\u00e0 Ti\u00ean Islands had 1,055 inhabitants.<ref name=\"nghidinh\" /> In early 2012, the island had more than 420 households with nearly 1,800 people.<ref name=\"ca\">{{in lang|vi}} {{cite news |title=\u0102n T\u1ebft tr\u00ean qu\u1ea7n \u0111\u1ea3o H\u1ea3i T\u1eb7c |author=Th\u00e1i B\u00ecnh |url=http://www.cand.com.vn/vi-VN/xahoi/2012/1/164672.cand |publisher=C\u00f4ng an Nh\u00e2n d\u00e2n online |date=January 31, 2012 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6D53v2cLa?url=http://www.cand.com.vn/vi-VN/xahoi/2012/1/164672.cand |archivedate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nLocal residents live mainly by fishing.<ref name=\"tp\" /> In 2011, the total output of marine products was 22,000 tons. Per capita income is about 48 million [[Vietnamese \u0111\u1ed3ng|\u0111\u1ed3ng]] (nearly 2,300 U.S dollars). Furthermore, water shortage in the [[dry season]] has been solved thanks to a freshwater reservoir.<ref name=\"ca\" /> In 2007 and 2008, Kien Giang provincial government laid down a policy to lease a number of islands of Ha Tien Islands to develop marine eco-tourism.<ref name=\"badm\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Ha Tien Islands}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ha Tien Islands}}\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Ki\u00ean Giang Province]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Gulf of Thailand]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H%C3%A0_Ti%C3%AAn_Islands"}
{"title_page": "Hinako Islands", "text_new": "The '''Hinako Islands''' are a group of small islands off the west coast of [[Nias Island]] in the Sirombu District of the [[West Nias Regency]], part of the [[North Sumatra Province]] of [[Indonesia]].\n\nThe islands are a popular [[surfing]] destination, specifically [[Bawa Island]], and nearby [[Asu Island]]. The waves at Bawa favor a northwest wind and the waves at Asu favor a southeast wind. The two islands are approximately 45 minutes apart by speedboat.\n\nThe waves at Bawa were revealed in magazine articles and a surf film in 1994, featuring surfers [[Tom Curren]] (USA) and Francis Desmond \"Frankie\" Oberholzer ([[South Africa|RSA]]) riding some of the biggest waves ever seen in Indonesia at that time photographed by Ted Grambeau (AUS) and filmed by [[Sonny Miller]] (USA).<ref>http://www.surfline.com/surf-news/revisiting-tom-currens-infamous-94-session-at-indos-biggest-right-tube----on-a-57-fireball-fish-1_101288/</ref>\n\nThe breaking pattern of the waves at both Bawa and Asu was significantly affected by the nearby [[2005 Nias\u2013Simeulue earthquake|earthquake]] of 28 March 2005, measuring 8.6 on the [[Richter magnitude scale|Richter scale]]. The seafloor in the region was raised by up to two meters and over 900 people were killed on Nias Island.<ref>[[2005 Nias\u2013Simeulue earthquake]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=May 2017}}\n\nThe Hinako Islands have long been infamous for [[malaria]], and have few accommodations for visitors.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kjoVRBrrw5UC&pg=PT170|title=Surfing Indonesia|author=Lorca Lueras|isbn=978-962-593-853-0|page=170}}\n\n;Notes\n<references />\n\n{{coord|0.833333|97.333336|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n\n\n{{NSumatra-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Hinako Islands''' are a group of small islands off the west coast of [[Nias Island]] in the Sirombu District of the [[West Nias Regency]], part of the [[North Sumatra Province]] of [[Indonesia]].\n\nThe islands are a popular [[surfing]] destination, specifically [[Bawa Island]], and nearby [[Asu Island]]. The waves at Bawa favor a northwest wind and the waves at Asu favor a southeast wind. The two islands are approximately 45 minutes apart by speedboat.\n\nThe waves at Bawa were revealed in magazine articles and a surf film in 1994, featuring surfers [[Tom Curren]] (USA) and Francis Desmond \"Frankie\" Oberholzer ([[South Africa|RSA]]) riding some of the biggest waves ever seen in Indonesia at that time photographed by Ted Grambeau (AUS) and filmed by [[Sonny Miller]] (USA).<ref>http://www.surfline.com/surf-news/revisiting-tom-currens-infamous-94-session-at-indos-biggest-right-tube----on-a-57-fireball-fish-1_101288/</ref>\n\nThe breaking pattern of the waves at both Bawa and Asu was significantly affected by the nearby [[2005 Nias\u2013Simeulue earthquake|earthquake]] of 28 March 2005, measuring 8.6 on the [[Richter magnitude scale|Richter scale]]. The seafloor in the region was raised by up to two meters and over 900 people were killed on Nias Island.<ref>[[2005 Nias\u2013Simeulue earthquake]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=May 2017}}\n\nThe Hinako Islands have long been infamous for [[malaria]], and have few accommodations for visitors.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kjoVRBrrw5UC&pg=PT170|title=Surfing Indonesia|author=Lorca Lueras|isbn=978-962-593-853-0|page=170}}\n\n;Notes\n<references />\n\n{{coord|0.833333|97.333336|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n\n\n{{NSumatra-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hinako_Islands"}
